definitions.definition: To lift (something) and take it to another place; to transport (something) by lifting.
To notionally transfer from one place (such as a country, book, or column) to another.
examples: to carry the war from Greece into Asia
to carry an account to the ledger

definitions.definition: To convey by extension or continuance; to extend.
examples: The builders are going to carry the chimney through the roof.
They would have carried the road ten miles further, but ran out of materials.

definitions.definition: To move; to convey using force
To lead or guide .
To stock or supply (something); to have in store .
examples: The corner drugstore doesn’t carry his favorite brand of aspirin.

definitions.definition: To adopt (something); take (something) over .
examples: I think I can carry Smith’s work while she is out.

definitions.definition: To adopt or resolve on, especially in a deliberative assembly
examples: The court carries that motion.

definitions.definition: In an addition , to transfer the quantity in excess of what is countable in the units in a column to the column immediately to the left in order to be added there.
examples: Five and nine are fourteen; carry the one to the tens place.

definitions.definition: To have , hold , possess or maintain (something).
examples: Always carry sufficient insurance to protect against a loss.

definitions.definition: To be transmitted ; to travel .
examples: The sound of the bells carried for miles on the wind.

definitions.definition: To insult , to diss .
To capture a ship by coming alongside and boarding .
To transport (the ball) whilst maintaining possession.
For the ball, having been hit in the air, to reach a fielder without touching the ground (whether or not the fielder catches it).
To have on one’s person.
examples: She always carries a purse.
Marsupials carry their young in a pouch

definitions.definition: To be pregnant (with).
examples: The doctor said she’s carrying twins.

definitions.definition: To have propulsive power; to propel.
examples: A gun or mortar carries well.

definitions.definition: To hold the head; said of a horse.
examples: to carry well, i.e. to hold the head high, with arching neck

definitions.definition: To have earth or frost stick to the feet when running, as a hare .
To bear or uphold successfully, especially through conflict, for example a leader or principle
To succeed in (e.g. a contest); to succeed in; to win.
examples: The Tories carried the election.

definitions.definition: To get possession of by force; to capture.
To contain; to comprise; have a particular aspect; to show or exhibit
To bear (oneself); to behave or conduct.
To bear the charges or burden of holding or having, as stocks, merchandise, etc., from one time to another.
examples: to carry a life insurance

definitions.definition: To have a weapon on one's person; to be armed .
To be disproportionately responsible for a team's success or for counteracting teammates' underperformance.
examples: Despite zero goals and zero assists, she still stands out for carrying her team's defense.
The other outfielders had no hustle, but fortunately the centerfielder carried them.
He absolutely carried , to the point of killing the entire enemy team by himself.

definitions.definition: To physically transport (in the general sense, not necessarily by lifting)
examples: Will you carry me to town?

definitions.definition: To bear a firearm , such as a gun .
examples: A holster can help you carry in confidence, knowing that your weapon is secure and close at hand.
